Valentin Yumashev, the son-in-law of former Russian leader Mr Yeltsin who helped Putin come to power, has quit his role as a Kremlin adviser. His departure removes one of the last links to Mr Yeltsin's rule which was characterised by liberal reforms and opening up Russia to the West. This latest resignation comes amid bubbling discontent around the war. In March, Anatoly Chubais, another senior Yeltsin-era figure, left his role as Kremlin special envoy and earlier this month a diplomat in Russia's mission to the United Nations resigned over the war. FOLLOW BELOW FOR UPDATES...